00:05:00.030 --> 00:05:04.500
Today, I'm going to talk
about modern Arabic poetry

00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:07.420
and why the Arab regimes
should never tell

00:05:07.420 --> 00:05:10.780
and Arab poet not to write.

00:05:10.780 --> 00:05:13.880
Poetry has played an essential

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:16.920
in Arabic culture since
pre-Islamic times.

00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:18.860
Dating back to the sixth century,

00:05:18.860 --> 00:05:21.270
also known as a the
Jahiliyyah period,

00:05:21.270 --> 00:05:25.660
poets were the political
spokespersons of the tribe.

00:05:25.660 --> 00:05:30.800
Each tribe had its own
poets to write its history,

00:05:30.800 --> 00:05:37.590
defend its stature, and be
its representatives and voice.

00:05:37.590 --> 00:05:41.120
Poets held esteem positions
in society.

00:05:41.120 --> 00:05:45.030
Not only to document the
ins and outs of their tribes

00:05:45.030 --> 00:05:47.900
and defend its identity, but also

00:05:47.900 --> 00:05:51.370
to promote their tribe
among the other tribes.

00:05:51.370 --> 00:05:57.280
Arab poets described in carefully
crafted verse the political

00:05:57.280 --> 00:06:01.980
and cultural aspects of their
Bedouin society and used poetry

00:06:01.980 --> 00:06:06.960
to praise the tribe
or attack its rivals.

00:06:06.960 --> 00:06:14.590 position:56%
Praise, boasting, satire, and elegy,
were among the major functions

00:06:14.590 --> 00:06:16.210
of their pre-Islam
[foreign word], the oath.

00:06:16.210 --> 00:06:24.930
Pre-Islamic poetry was oral and its
performative nature demanded rhyme

00:06:24.930 --> 00:06:30.200 position:56%
and meter to draw the attention of
the audience through its musicality.

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:35.240
Tribes competed through
the talents of their poets

00:06:35.240 --> 00:06:37.180
who would gather every year

00:06:37.180 --> 00:06:40.510
to present their finest
poems to the public.

00:06:40.510 --> 00:06:45.290
The stronger the tribe,
the more powerful the voice

00:06:45.290 --> 00:06:47.860
of its poets became.

00:06:47.860 --> 00:06:51.280
By the same token, the more
gifted a tribe's poets,

00:06:51.280 --> 00:06:56.410
the louder its voice
among other tribes.

00:06:56.410 --> 00:07:00.910
Poets moved men to go to war
and recounted their exploits

00:07:00.910 --> 00:07:03.630
after their return
from the battlefield.

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:10.290
If the tribe won a battle, its
poets wrote verses in its praise

00:07:10.290 --> 00:07:15.710
which quickly traveled among
other tribes raising its status.

00:07:15.710 --> 00:07:20.230
If it lost, poets wrote
elegies and cited the tribe

00:07:20.230 --> 00:07:24.320
to avenge its heroic,
slaughtered kinsmen.

00:07:28.770 --> 00:07:34.920
Arabs consider poetry one of their
supreme, cultural accomplishments.

00:07:34.920 --> 00:07:38.260
All though modern Arabic
poetry continued to retain some

00:07:38.260 --> 00:07:40.910
of the major functions of the
pre-Islamic [foreign word],

00:07:40.910 --> 00:07:46.350
its deeply concerned about
questions that pertain

00:07:46.350 --> 00:07:49.330 position:56%
to the identity and future of Arabs.

00:07:49.330 --> 00:07:55.740
And here are some of the
functions of modern Arabic poetry.

00:07:55.740 --> 00:08:00.910
Another function is questioning
the political status quo

00:08:00.910 --> 00:08:04.070
and giving voice to the
silenced, voiceless multitude.

00:08:04.070 --> 00:08:10.780
Modern Arab poets, like the
Egyptian, Ahmad abd al-Muti-Hijazi,

00:08:10.780 --> 00:08:16.020
the Syrian, Nizar Qabbani,
the Egyptian, Fatma Kandil,

00:08:16.020 --> 00:08:20.160
and the Iraqi, Muzaffar
al-Nawwab, wrote poetry for decades

00:08:20.160 --> 00:08:24.520
to guard the collective memory,
to preserve our Arabic language,

00:08:24.520 --> 00:08:29.390
and to address the challenges
of our culture and society.

00:08:29.390 --> 00:08:32.740
In so doing, they were also
questioning our understanding

00:08:32.740 --> 00:08:37.470
of history and rewriting from
the perspective of the people,

00:08:37.470 --> 00:08:39.670
not their authoritarian regimes.

00:08:39.670 --> 00:08:44.620 position:56%
Because these poets opposed their
governments and incited their people

00:08:44.620 --> 00:08:48.430
through poetry to reject their
enslavement in a life void

00:08:48.430 --> 00:08:53.320
of basic human rights, they
were often exiled, imprisoned,

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:58.770
dismissed from official positions,
and harassed by the Arab state.

00:08:58.770 --> 00:09:03.110
Therefore, the experience of a
wandering human being in exile,

00:09:03.110 --> 00:09:07.830
or diaspora, and the search for
the lost paradise, the homeland,

00:09:07.830 --> 00:09:12.070
is a popular theme in
modern Arabic poetry.

00:09:12.070 --> 00:09:18.650
Poetry offered these poets and the
Arab individual a space to grieve,

00:09:18.650 --> 00:09:24.030
to criticize the status quo,
to dream of a better life,

00:09:24.030 --> 00:09:28.120
to meditate, and to feel.

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:34.610
Poetry is one of the few remaining
expressions of art and beauty

00:09:34.610 --> 00:09:39.190
for the Arab individual
in this tragic age.

00:09:39.190 --> 00:09:47.280
Poems do not lie and if the future
looks dim, poetry will say so.

00:09:47.280 --> 00:09:52.880
For those reasons and
many more, Arab regimes

00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:57.950
and rulers should never tell
an Arab poet not to write.

00:09:57.950 --> 00:10:02.790
Because poetry invites
creativity and imagination.

00:10:02.790 --> 00:10:09.480
And Arab regimes do not want
their people to think or dream.

00:10:09.480 --> 00:10:14.910
They want ignorant, obedient
nations living in fear.

00:10:14.910 --> 00:10:19.580
Writing poetry is searching
for the key

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:23.850
that has been lost
to open closed doors.

00:10:23.850 --> 00:10:29.120
Poetry invites readers
to find their keys

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:33.070
or break their closed doors
and set themselves free.

00:10:33.070 --> 00:10:38.930
The price of freedom in the
Arab world is hefty for sure

00:10:38.930 --> 00:10:44.640
and poets are the first to know.

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:50.810
Here are the poets I'll
be talking about today.

00:10:50.810 --> 00:10:55.690
Qabbani, Nizar Qabbani, Ahmad
abd al-Muti Hijazi, Fatma Kandil,

00:10:55.690 --> 00:11:00.220
Muzaffar al-Nawwab, among
many other Arab poets,

00:11:00.220 --> 00:11:05.000
wrote poetry to preserve Arabic
language and the poetic tradition

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:10.680
as well as to address universal
causes that are of utmost concern

00:11:10.680 --> 00:11:16.360
to humanity, and especially
to the Arab citizen.

00:11:16.360 --> 00:11:20.450
They feared for their fellow Arabs
and their language and heritage.

00:11:20.450 --> 00:11:24.540
And they used their
only weapon, poetry,

00:11:24.540 --> 00:11:27.350
to voice their concerns
and shape their stances.

00:11:27.350 --> 00:11:32.450
They saw poetry as
a platform to fight

00:11:32.450 --> 00:11:35.780
against dictators and oppressors.

00:11:35.780 --> 00:11:39.110
They warned against the
loss of Arab identity

00:11:39.110 --> 00:11:45.180
and anticipated a grand future if
Arab citizens and poets continued

00:11:45.180 --> 00:11:48.040
to live in fear of oppression.

00:11:48.040 --> 00:11:51.530
For change to take
place in the Arab world,

00:11:51.530 --> 00:11:55.640
fear of repression must
be eliminated and death

00:11:55.640 --> 00:12:00.080
and ruin should be expected
before the sky rains

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:02.830
and the land can be fertile again.

00:12:02.830 --> 00:12:05.710
The first poet I'll be talking

00:12:05.710 --> 00:12:09.260
about today is Nizar
Qabbani, the Syrian poet.

00:12:09.260 --> 00:12:13.850
Nizar Qabbani was born in 1923
[foreign word] in Damascus

00:12:13.850 --> 00:12:18.210
and he died in London in 1998.

00:12:18.210 --> 00:12:20.670
He wrote over 40 books
of poetry and prose.

00:12:20.670 --> 00:12:24.600 position:56%
And his poetry has been celebrated
and translated in several languages.

00:12:24.600 --> 00:12:31.500
He's often referred to as the poet
of the people or the romantic poet.

00:12:31.500 --> 00:12:33.770
So, who is Qabbani?

00:12:33.770 --> 00:12:41.730
Let's read some stanzas of
his poetry and discuss some

00:12:41.730 --> 00:12:43.870
of the major themes and functions.

00:12:43.870 --> 00:12:48.260
The following stanza here
-- this is Nizar Qabbani --

00:12:48.260 --> 00:12:50.140
We are Accused of Terrorism.

00:12:50.140 --> 00:12:56.050
Because of limitations of
time, I selected some stanzas.

00:12:56.050 --> 00:13:00.700
The following stanza is from his
poem, We are Accused of Terrorism

00:13:00.700 --> 00:13:04.620
and in this poem, he voices his
disappointment with the status quo

00:13:04.620 --> 00:13:07.930
in the Arab world which
reflects that of Arabic poetry

00:13:07.930 --> 00:13:10.320
and how poets are treated.

00:13:10.320 --> 00:13:18.280
He says, "You will not find with me
a secret poem or a secret language

00:13:18.280 --> 00:13:23.010
or secret books I imprison
inside the doors.

00:13:23.010 --> 00:13:26.180
I do not have even one poem walking

00:13:26.180 --> 00:13:29.210
on the streets while
wearing a hijab.

00:13:29.210 --> 00:13:33.520
We are accused of terrorism
if we write about the homeland

00:13:33.520 --> 00:13:38.960
that forbids us from buying a
newspaper or hearing the news

00:13:38.960 --> 00:13:43.580
about a homeland where all
birds are banned from singing,

00:13:43.580 --> 00:13:46.220
about a homeland whose
writers are accustomed

00:13:46.220 --> 00:13:50.710
to writing the air
out of extreme horror.

00:13:50.710 --> 00:13:55.950
We're banned from writing about
a homeland that resembles poetry

00:13:55.950 --> 00:13:59.450
in our country, improvised,
imported,

00:13:59.450 --> 00:14:05.220 position:56%
and loose of foreign tongue and
soul and having no beginning or end,

00:14:05.220 --> 00:14:13.050
detached from man and land
or from the plight of man."

00:14:13.050 --> 00:14:16.420
According to Qabanni, nations
that fail to nurture their poets

00:14:16.420 --> 00:14:18.090
to defend and preserve
their language

00:14:18.090 --> 00:14:23.450
and literature will have no
civilizations to be remembered.

00:14:23.450 --> 00:14:26.740
Qabbani realizes how
fear governs Arabic life

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:29.760
and threatens Arabic
literature as well.

00:14:29.760 --> 00:14:35.010 position:56%
Arab writers and poets like
Qabbani, lived and live in a country

00:14:35.010 --> 00:14:37.950
that forbids them from
living a normal life.

00:14:37.950 --> 00:14:44.520
It forbids them even from buying
newspaper or hearing the news.

00:14:44.520 --> 00:14:47.560
It turns the poets
down and bans them

00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:52.000
from writing poetry,
from speaking out.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:55.930
However, Qabbani insists on
writing about this homeland

00:14:55.930 --> 00:14:59.650
because it too is a victim.

00:14:59.650 --> 00:15:02.630
Qabbani refuses to oppress his bird

00:15:02.630 --> 00:15:06.770
by using a secret language
to imprison the poem.

00:15:06.770 --> 00:15:13.630
Rather, he insists on writing naked
free poems about this homeland

00:15:13.630 --> 00:15:16.290
and its displaced people.

00:15:16.290 --> 00:15:19.750
If Arabic poetry is reduced
to improvised, imported,

00:15:19.750 --> 00:15:22.470
and loose words of
foreign tongue and soil,

00:15:22.470 --> 00:15:25.340
then Arabs will have lost not
only a part of our culture

00:15:25.340 --> 00:15:29.410
and thought, but also
their identity.

00:15:29.410 --> 00:15:34.470
Therefore, writing poetry for
Qabbani is an act of resistance

00:15:34.470 --> 00:15:37.030
against erasing an Arab identity

00:15:37.030 --> 00:15:40.040
and stripping its people
from their language.

00:15:40.040 --> 00:15:46.460
I quote, "Qabbani's hailed by
the Arabs to be a modern poet

00:15:46.460 --> 00:15:52.230
of stature, whose poetry is read,
put to music, sung, and memorized.

00:15:52.230 --> 00:15:55.450
This is the most important
testimony to his genius."

00:15:55.450 --> 00:15:56.750
End of quote.

00:15:56.750 --> 00:15:58.050
J. Gatin [phonetic spelling].

00:15:58.050 --> 00:16:04.600
Qabbani said in 1948

00:16:04.600 --> 00:16:07.940
when he published his first
collection the following --

00:16:07.940 --> 00:16:12.070
and it says a lot about
him being a poet.

00:16:12.070 --> 00:16:16.590
I want art to be the property
of all people, like air, water,

00:16:16.590 --> 00:16:19.500
and the song of the sparrow.

00:16:19.500 --> 00:16:22.220
I dream about a poetic city.

00:16:22.220 --> 00:16:27.000
If the reader feels that my heart
becomes his heart and that I become

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.860
for him a mouth and throat,

00:16:29.860 --> 00:16:33.600
then I certainly shall have
achieved my aim, that is,

00:16:33.600 --> 00:16:39.230
to make poetry exist in every
house besides bread and water.

00:16:39.230 --> 00:16:44.930
The Arab authoritarian states
will continue indefinitely to hunt

00:16:44.930 --> 00:16:50.810
down poets, call them terrorists,
and try to buy them off.

00:16:50.810 --> 00:16:52.110
But as [foreign name] says,

00:16:52.110 --> 00:16:57.210
"The dictator perishes
and the poet remains."

00:16:57.210 --> 00:17:01.380
Qabbani maintains that writing free
poetry is the key to combat fear,

00:17:01.380 --> 00:17:05.980 position:56%
to fight oppression, and to preserve
what remained of our Arabism.

00:17:05.980 --> 00:17:12.020
This is what he can do as a poet.

00:17:13.750 --> 00:17:19.890
My second poet is Ahmad
abd al-Muti-Hijazi.

00:17:19.890 --> 00:17:24.800
Ahmad abd al-Muti-Hijazi
was born in the village

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:27.960
of [foreign word] Al-Menoufiya,
Egypt, 1935.

00:17:27.960 --> 00:17:31.740
His family was one of the
middle-class peasant families

00:17:31.740 --> 00:17:36.510
in the Egyptian countryside where
he was educated and brought up.

00:17:36.510 --> 00:17:41.220
He wrote seven collections of
poetry between 1959 and 2011

00:17:41.220 --> 00:17:45.190
and he has written 25
books in prose as well.

00:17:45.190 --> 00:17:49.190
His poetry has been translated
into several languages.

