Creatures of the Ninth
Kingdom, in 1989.

00:17:59.560 --> 00:18:04.840
This Ninth Kingdom refers to
[foreign name] dictatorship.

00:18:04.840 --> 00:18:08.460
In this poem, Hijazi gives shape
to the feelings of loss and despair

00:18:08.460 --> 00:18:13.170
in the life characterized by
fear where he is, I quote,

00:18:13.170 --> 00:18:16.810
"At his closest to
modernist dramatization."

00:18:16.810 --> 00:18:22.900
"Nothing remained of the glory
of this country but a bar.

00:18:22.900 --> 00:18:26.870
Nothing remained of the state
but a policeman showing off

00:18:26.870 --> 00:18:31.020
under the last light
his long shadow one time

00:18:31.020 --> 00:18:34.480
and another time his short shadow.

00:18:34.480 --> 00:18:38.900
Fear has become a homeland, a
currency, a national language,

00:18:38.900 --> 00:18:42.390
anthem and identity,
and elected council.

00:18:42.390 --> 00:18:45.120
And fear has become its savior."

00:18:45.120 --> 00:18:50.500
According to Hijazi, the country

00:18:50.500 --> 00:18:54.600
that once lived Arab nationalism
has been reduced to a bar populated

00:18:54.600 --> 00:18:58.460
by chattering drunks and
a state of policemen.

00:18:58.460 --> 00:19:04.520
There is nothing to be proud of
about Egypt according this stanza,

00:19:04.520 --> 00:19:09.110
which has become a wasteland
devoid of democracy, freedom,

00:19:09.110 --> 00:19:13.200
morals, ethics, and security.

00:19:13.200 --> 00:19:16.240
Hijazi complicates the
image of his wasteland

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:19.910
by projecting fear into the scene.

00:19:19.910 --> 00:19:27.050
Fear has become the dominant theme
in every aspect of life, as we see.

00:19:27.050 --> 00:19:31.730
More importantly, it's
become the homeland.

00:19:31.730 --> 00:19:35.570
Dominating every aspect of
life in the Ninth Kingdom,

00:19:35.570 --> 00:19:38.510
fear's now the religion and
the god everyone worships

00:19:38.510 --> 00:19:41.680
and fears in the Arab world.

00:19:41.680 --> 00:19:46.110
Instead of promoting security,
Arab rulers use fear and oppression

00:19:46.110 --> 00:19:50.710
to terrorize their people and
oppose their authority over them.

00:19:50.710 --> 00:19:53.860
Failing to maintain an
identity or speak a language

00:19:53.860 --> 00:19:57.340
that doesn't involve
fear, Hijazi distrusts

00:19:57.340 --> 00:20:03.570
and despises everything
he sees and he hears.

00:20:03.570 --> 00:20:13.550 position:56%
In another stanza from another poem,
Cement Trees, and commenting on fear

00:20:13.550 --> 00:20:18.280
and hunting poets --
"The wind comes and goes

00:20:18.280 --> 00:20:20.930
without crossing this
silence or being able

00:20:20.930 --> 00:20:23.160
to convey the villages' distress.

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:24.640
And the shipwrecked vessels

00:20:24.640 --> 00:20:30.850
and these cement trees are
everywhere showing off and roaring,

00:20:30.850 --> 00:20:35.900
like demons, and hunting birds that
fall like stones in the radars.

00:20:35.900 --> 00:20:38.870
Or hanging them from
the fuzz of their necks

00:20:38.870 --> 00:20:42.500 position:56%
on the wires of the spying machines.

00:20:42.500 --> 00:20:47.720
From our balconies, we know
that the birds are dying now

00:20:47.720 --> 00:20:52.890
in these skies when
the flock crashes.

00:20:52.890 --> 00:20:54.930
Hijazi watches the
villages in distress

00:20:54.930 --> 00:20:59.900
and shipwrecked vessels while
the wind comes and goes uncaring.

00:20:59.900 --> 00:21:02.990
Life seems to go on without
sympathy for the ordeal

00:21:02.990 --> 00:21:06.560
of a poet whose life
came to the birds.

00:21:06.560 --> 00:21:10.790
Writers express the struggle of
the individual in their societies

00:21:10.790 --> 00:21:13.480 position:56%
and oppose their oppressive regimes.

00:21:13.480 --> 00:21:16.700 position:56%
These regimes are like cement trees.

00:21:16.700 --> 00:21:18.160
They suffocate the individual

00:21:18.160 --> 00:21:21.430
and hide his screams
between closed doors.

00:21:21.430 --> 00:21:23.480
They're like demons
which hunt human beings

00:21:23.480 --> 00:21:26.580
and throw them mercilessly
to the grounds.

00:21:26.580 --> 00:21:30.020
Hijazi criticizes the Arab
regimes for spying on writers,

00:21:30.020 --> 00:21:34.570 position:56%
torturing them, and censoring and
banning their works from the public.

00:21:34.570 --> 00:21:37.990
The poem reflects the
disappointed pessimistic

00:21:37.990 --> 00:21:42.390
and oppressed Hijazi's
poetry in the 1980's.

00:21:42.390 --> 00:21:45.450
Hijazi expresses opposition
to the lack of freedom

00:21:45.450 --> 00:21:50.710
of expression throughout the Arab
world, particularly in Egypt.

00:21:50.710 --> 00:21:55.280
Writers are hunted down and
their lives are monitored.

00:21:55.280 --> 00:21:57.320
Hijazi sees the Arab
world as a wasteland

00:21:57.320 --> 00:22:02.250
that oppresses its citizens
and silences their voices.

00:22:02.250 --> 00:22:08.260
That's why poets speak out
on behalf of their people.

00:22:08.260 --> 00:22:17.680
My third poet is my favorite
poet, Muzaffar al-Nawwab.

00:22:17.680 --> 00:22:26.880
Muzaffar al-Nawwab was born
in 1934 in Bagdad, Iraq.

00:22:26.880 --> 00:22:31.730
He spent over 40 years in exile
voicing his strong opposition to

00:22:31.730 --> 00:22:37.620
and criticism of authoritarian Arab
regimes and Western imperialism.

00:22:37.620 --> 00:22:40.520
His words I quote,
"Are so controversial

00:22:40.520 --> 00:22:42.090
that they cannot be
printed officially

00:22:42.090 --> 00:22:45.420
in the Arab world are
under an interdiction.

00:22:45.420 --> 00:22:50.080
His poetry readings circulating
on cassettes are photocopied

00:22:50.080 --> 00:22:52.740
and passed from hand to hand."

00:22:52.740 --> 00:22:55.170
End of Quote.

00:22:55.170 --> 00:22:57.080
And now, the age of the internet,

00:22:57.080 --> 00:22:59.840
his poetry is available
online, of course.

00:22:59.840 --> 00:23:04.560
Although, Arab governments
continue to censor any threatening,

00:23:04.560 --> 00:23:08.250 position:56%
poetic material like that of Nawwab.

00:23:15.380 --> 00:23:19.150 position:56%
This is a quotation about al-Nawwab.

00:23:19.150 --> 00:23:23.070
Most central to al-Nawwab's
project as a poet,

00:23:23.070 --> 00:23:27.680
is the very concerted dedications
to the composition, orchestration,

00:23:27.680 --> 00:23:31.720
and performance of poetry
that is meant to stir

00:23:31.720 --> 00:23:37.650 position:56%
and agitate his audience, to provoke
and arouse a wide rate of emotions,

00:23:37.650 --> 00:23:43.610
childlike wonderment, nostalgic
longing, sensuous arousal, disgust,

00:23:43.610 --> 00:23:49.740
rage, all in some way meant to be
intimately related back to the fate

00:23:49.740 --> 00:23:53.250
of the contemporary
Arab world as a matter

00:23:53.250 --> 00:23:55.800
of urgent collective concern."

00:23:59.910 --> 00:24:05.200
A major recurring theme in the
following stanzas from With Wine

00:24:05.200 --> 00:24:09.970
and Grief is My Heart Intoxicated
is in the words, grief and longing

00:24:09.970 --> 00:24:13.030
for his homeland in diaspora.

00:24:15.290 --> 00:24:21.510 position:56%
And since you see it in translation,
I can read it in Arabic.

00:24:21.510 --> 00:25:35.670
[ Foreign Speaking ]

00:25:35.670 --> 00:25:44.680 position:56%
al-Nawwab finds no keys in
diaspora to free him from his grief.

00:25:44.680 --> 00:25:49.040
He wanders in exile and wonders
if there is still a chance

00:25:49.040 --> 00:25:54.510
to rescue what remained of the
homeland, its identity, and future.

00:25:54.510 --> 00:25:58.740
In this poem, al-Nawwab treats
themes of grief, oppression,

00:25:58.740 --> 00:26:02.060
ruthlessness, and homesickness.

00:26:02.060 --> 00:26:04.270
In the Arab world, poets

00:26:04.270 --> 00:26:09.380
like al-Nawwab become a
ruthless plant living,

00:26:09.380 --> 00:26:13.130
or pretending to live in water.

00:26:13.130 --> 00:26:19.760
This plant longs for any dust
to call home but it finds none.

00:26:19.760 --> 00:26:23.610
Knowing what it means to be
a ruthless plant in water,

00:26:23.610 --> 00:26:28.560
Nawwab looks at a sleeping
baby, hears him cooing

00:26:28.560 --> 00:26:33.170
and wishes he does not
grow up to be as listless

00:26:33.170 --> 00:26:36.510
and ruthless as the poet, himself.

00:26:36.510 --> 00:26:42.630
He prays the child grows up to find
himself a place he can call home.

00:26:42.630 --> 00:26:46.010
Because in the Arab world, there
is no privilege that equals

00:26:46.010 --> 00:26:50.130
that of truly having a homeland.

00:26:50.130 --> 00:26:57.370
Having none, Nawwab realizes how
open wounds are not meant to heal

00:26:57.370 --> 00:27:01.140
and therefore they
become the memory of loss.

00:27:01.140 --> 00:27:07.500
Grief runs in al-Nawwab's blood
and drowning in a ruin sea

00:27:07.500 --> 00:27:11.790
of infinite pain is now the port.

00:27:11.790 --> 00:27:15.830
And Nawwab knows and
reminds us that the mud

00:27:15.830 --> 00:27:20.880
of love in our land is harmed.

00:27:20.880 --> 00:27:25.720 position:56%
If the dirtiest mud sprouts jasmine,
when it's nurtured with love,

00:27:25.720 --> 00:27:30.240 position:56%
what would the best Arab mud sprout?

00:27:30.240 --> 00:27:33.620
And Nawwab weeps for
the lost paradise

00:27:33.620 --> 00:27:36.900
and the lost potential
of Arab youth.

00:27:36.900 --> 00:27:41.880
A youth oppressed and stripped
from its basic human rights.

00:27:41.880 --> 00:27:47.320
What does the future have
in store for this baby?

00:27:47.320 --> 00:27:53.070
No one knows but the poet
is worried and rightly so.

00:27:53.070 --> 00:27:57.020
For no one knows what it means
to have a place to call home more

00:27:57.020 --> 00:28:04.650
than a ruthless plant in water.

00:28:06.510 --> 00:28:27.840
[ Foreign Speaking ]

00:28:27.840 --> 00:28:31.230
I threw my keys in the Tigris
in the days of longing.

00:28:31.230 --> 00:28:36.540
And now in diaspora, there
remains no key to unlock me.

00:28:36.540 --> 00:28:40.940
Here I am, locked up but outspoken.

00:28:40.940 --> 00:28:45.040
He who was locked up in longing
and was lost on the sidewalks

00:28:45.040 --> 00:28:52.530
of al-Shaam, shall relate to me.

00:28:52.530 --> 00:28:55.820
Those who share the poet's
experience of walking

00:28:55.820 --> 00:28:59.750
on the sidewalks of al-Shaam,
lost, sad, and alienated,

00:28:59.750 --> 00:29:03.970
would understand his words
and relate to his pains

00:29:03.970 --> 00:29:07.440
that no remedy can treat.

00:29:07.440 --> 00:29:12.260 position:56%
Despite being locked up in diaspora,
al-Nawwab continues to be outspoken.

00:29:12.260 --> 00:29:16.970
Many Arabs in the Arab
world and in the diaspora,

00:29:16.970 --> 00:29:20.900
relate to Nawwab's poetry and share
some aspects of his experience.

00:29:20.900 --> 00:29:28.520 position:56%
In another poem, the Old Tavern --
this is the last one by al-Nawwab --

00:29:28.520 --> 00:29:34.060
Nawwab reminds us all that as an
Arab poet, he rejects two things.

00:29:34.060 --> 00:29:40.390
And we shall see these two things.

00:29:40.390 --> 00:29:46.760
Oh lord, I have accepted all
things except humiliation

00:29:46.760 --> 00:29:50.100
and having my heart caged
in the sultan's palace.

00:29:50.100 --> 00:29:54.460
I was content that my lot in this
world be like that of a bird,

00:29:54.460 --> 00:29:59.560
but oh Lord, even birds
have homelands to return to.

00:29:59.560 --> 00:30:04.920 position:56%
But I am still flying over this
homeland stretching from sea to sea,

00:30:04.920 --> 00:30:10.510 position:56%
prisons pressed against one another,
one jailer huddling another.

00:30:10.510 --> 00:30:44.810
[ Foreign Speaking ]

00:30:44.810 --> 00:30:49.490
al-Nawwab projects two things,
humiliation and becoming the voice

00:30:49.490 --> 00:30:52.260
of the sultan instead
of that of the people.

00:30:52.260 --> 00:30:56.890
For a poet like Nawwab, the act of
writing poetry is a necessary act

00:30:56.890 --> 00:31:01.170
of resistance to maintain
a dignified life.

00:31:01.170 --> 00:31:04.310
Like a bird, he needs
to return home.

00:31:04.310 --> 00:31:08.450 position:56%
However, because of his poetry,
he's destined to weep over the ruins

00:31:08.450 --> 00:31:11.160
of the Arab world which has turned

00:31:11.160 --> 00:31:17.980
into prison stretching
from to sea to sea.

00:31:35.050 --> 00:31:37.830
Now, I'll be talking
about Nazir Qabbani --

00:31:37.830 --> 00:31:39.190
coming back -- Nazir Qabbani.

00:31:39.190 --> 00:31:46.390
The complete poetry for
political abduction incident.

00:31:46.390 --> 00:31:49.300
This poem speaks afresh of the
status quo in the Arab world

00:31:49.300 --> 00:31:52.370
and more specifically
to the refugee crisis

00:31:52.370 --> 00:31:56.730
in Syria despite being
written some 40 years ago.

00:31:56.730 --> 00:31:59.720
So, it's a very interesting poem.

00:31:59.720 --> 00:32:03.200
There are a few quotations --

00:32:03.200 --> 00:32:07.480
stanzas, of course because
it's a very long poem.

00:32:07.480 --> 00:32:11.240
Forgive us, our blood has
been shed since we were born.

00:32:11.240 --> 00:32:14.570
A thousand policemen
are on our papers.

00:32:14.570 --> 00:32:17.440
They shot us but we did not fall.

00:32:17.440 --> 00:32:21.840 position:56%
They tried to cut our legs to hinder
us from crawling but we stood up.

00:32:21.840 --> 00:32:27.160
They cut off our hands, so that we
cannot hold the pens but we wrote.

00:32:27.160 --> 00:32:30.370
They tried to convince us
that poetry is disbelief

00:32:30.370 --> 00:32:33.720
so we became disbelievers.

00:32:33.720 --> 00:32:38.270
Forgive us if we urinate on all
the statues that fill the squares

00:32:38.270 --> 00:32:42.860
of the city and all the images
that the police post forcibly

00:32:42.860 --> 00:32:47.190
and all the shops of the
city and all the slogans

00:32:47.190 --> 00:32:50.690
at which the children of
the city throw bricks.

00:32:50.690 --> 00:32:55.990
Forgive us if we pile like
sheep on the back of the ship,

00:32:55.990 --> 00:33:00.790
if we are scattered on all the
oceans for years and years.

00:33:00.790 --> 00:33:03.160
We did not find among
the Arab traders,

00:33:03.160 --> 00:33:08.120
a trader who would accept
to feed us our buy us.

00:33:08.120 --> 00:33:12.900
We did not find among the beautiful
Arab women a woman accepting

00:33:12.900 --> 00:33:15.280
to love us or free us.

00:33:15.280 --> 00:33:18.300
We did not find among
the Arab rebels a rebel

00:33:18.300 --> 00:33:22.730
who did not stab us with a knife.

00:33:22.730 --> 00:33:28.730
Forgive us, forgive us if we reject
everything, if we break everything,

00:33:28.730 --> 00:33:33.680
if we uproot everything, if
we throw our names at you

00:33:33.680 --> 00:33:37.510
because the valleys refused
us and the ports refused us.

00:33:37.510 --> 00:33:52.830
[ Foreign Speaking ]

00:33:52.830 --> 00:33:57.720
Qabbani questions the predominant
narratives of Arab history,

00:33:57.720 --> 00:34:01.000
religion, and literature.

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:05.100
He envisions the future of the
Arab world, either in a revolution

00:34:05.100 --> 00:34:09.930
where Arab leaders are attacked
in their palaces and ousted

00:34:09.930 --> 00:34:14.560
by the people or in a
major refugee crisis

00:34:14.560 --> 00:34:19.760
where the people are
ousted by their leaders.

00:34:19.760 --> 00:34:22.390
Qabbani defends the
people against the regime

00:34:22.390 --> 00:34:26.970
in this court trial
offering a complete account

00:34:26.970 --> 00:34:31.880
of an abduction incident that has
been taking place in the Arab world

00:34:31.880 --> 00:34:35.410
without being reported
or fairly tried.

00:34:35.410 --> 00:34:41.940
In ironically offering a poetic
apology to oppressor forces

00:34:41.940 --> 00:34:48.430
that crush Arab individuals
and undermine their humanity,

00:34:48.430 --> 00:34:52.790
Qabbani reveals a history
of systematic oppression

00:34:52.790 --> 00:34:59.110
in the Arab world and incites
his people to revolt if they want

00:34:59.110 --> 00:35:05.000
to stop this abduction from
continuing indefinitely.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:08.090
Towards the end of the
poem, Qabbani speaks

00:35:08.090 --> 00:35:13.860
for his scattered fellow
Arabs, particularly refugees

00:35:13.860 --> 00:35:19.430
who are denied entry by
Arab ports across the world.

00:35:19.430 --> 00:35:23.100
Qabbani tells the rulers of fear
in police states in the Arab world

00:35:23.100 --> 00:35:28.880
to forgive us because we couldn't
change the way things are,

00:35:28.880 --> 00:35:32.440 position:56%
because we let you shed our blood
to get drunk with it as Nawwab said,

00:35:32.440 --> 00:35:37.950
and because we gave you the
keys to our prison cells

00:35:37.950 --> 00:35:44.080
as obedient sheep you made us into.

00:35:44.080 --> 00:35:48.990
Until we face fear and take these
keys back and break these chains,

00:35:48.990 --> 00:35:56.190 position:56%
nothing will change and no prophets
will come to save us from the abyss.

00:35:56.190 --> 00:36:00.130
The sun of oppression will
continue to burn us alive

00:36:00.130 --> 00:36:02.140
and the world will continue

00:36:02.140 --> 00:36:06.540
to become less humane
with every passing day.

00:36:19.040 --> 00:36:25.480
I end my talk today
with Fatma Kandil.

00:36:25.480 --> 00:36:32.010
Fatma Kandil was born [foreign
word] in Cairo in 1958.

00:36:32.010 --> 00:36:33.950
She wrote several collections
of poetry

00:36:33.950 --> 00:36:36.570
and she's popular among
the young generation.

00:36:36.570 --> 00:36:42.100
The following stanzas are from her
poem, Thorny Gap, Suddenly Moving

00:36:42.100 --> 00:36:52.060
or Keys [foreign speaking]
in which she raises questions

00:36:52.060 --> 00:36:59.260
about the fate -- about fate and
free will and she addresses fear

00:36:59.260 --> 00:37:04.180
and how to better deal with it.

00:37:05.290 --> 00:37:12.830
The keys that open doors
are the keys that lock them.

00:37:12.830 --> 00:37:16.470
And the keys strangled
in chains have nothing

00:37:16.470 --> 00:37:19.120
but the drama of tinkling.

00:37:19.120 --> 00:37:24.930
But the key that dies in my
pocket reminds me it is time

00:37:24.930 --> 00:37:29.570
that I become a reasonable
woman who lives in a house

00:37:29.570 --> 00:37:32.510
without keys, without doors.

00:37:32.510 --> 00:38:38.040
[ Foreign Speaking ]

00:38:38.040 --> 00:38:40.420
Every day while I am on the express
metro, a rundown house flashes by,

00:38:40.420 --> 00:38:44.100
a wooden ladder leaning against it,

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:46.060
and a corrugated iron
door, always open.

00:38:46.060 --> 00:38:50.080
Every day, until it became my home.

00:38:50.080 --> 00:38:54.070
Fatma Kandil addresses the fear
controlling her life in general,

00:38:54.070 --> 00:39:00.080
her life as a female Arab
individual and uses the same keys

00:39:00.080 --> 00:39:05.110
that suffocate her life to
unlock the doors of the rooms

00:39:05.110 --> 00:39:11.910
that Arab citizens have been
confined in for centuries.

00:39:11.910 --> 00:39:20.340
She realizes that the house
she lives in only becomes here

00:39:20.340 --> 00:39:22.260
when she breaks its doors open.

00:39:22.260 --> 00:39:25.630
So, she no longer needs
keys to open these doors.

00:39:25.630 --> 00:39:30.630
Fear governs every aspect of
our life, public and personal.

00:39:30.630 --> 00:39:32.790
Therefore, Kandil realizes
that the keys

00:39:32.790 --> 00:39:38.970
that strangle her are the
keys that will set her free.

00:39:38.970 --> 00:39:45.900
Freeing the keys from the
chains is freeing oneself

00:39:45.900 --> 00:39:49.340
from the same chains,
no keys, no doors.

00:39:49.340 --> 00:39:55.150
That even the rundown
house which is a metaphor

00:39:55.150 --> 00:40:00.850
of what our life has become in this
tragic time, becomes free home.

00:40:00.850 --> 00:40:02.610
Kandil tells us that we glance

00:40:02.610 --> 00:40:11.550
at our rundown life everyday while
holding the keys to our freedom.

00:40:11.550 --> 00:40:13.870
But fear stops us from
acting, from changing.

00:40:13.870 --> 00:40:21.220
She reminds us that no one will
act on our behalf and if we want

00:40:21.220 --> 00:40:30.700
to turn this rundown house into a
home, we better take responsibility

00:40:30.700 --> 00:40:35.650
for our own fates, for our own
future, and make our own destiny.

00:40:35.650 --> 00:40:41.050
More important than this
realization, is that confession

00:40:41.050 --> 00:40:43.560
that our life is a rundown house.

00:40:43.560 --> 00:40:50.740
